1. Initialize arrays countY and countN to keep track of the number of Y and N characters in the input string.
2. Iterate through the string to update countY and countN accordingly.
3. Initialize a variable minPenalty to store the minimum penalty value found so far.
4. Iterate through the string again to check if the shop should close at each hour. If the shop is open and no customers arrive (countY[i] == 0 && countN[i] == 0), update minPenalty to the current hour (i + 1).
5. Return the minimum penalty value found.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n) because it only requires a single pass through the input string. The space complexity is O(n) because we need to store the count of Y and N characters in arrays countY and countN. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs simple operations and does not consume significant energy.

